## 3. Protected Attributes Under Australian Law

AI systems must not discriminate, directly or indirectly, on the basis of attributes protected by the following legislation:

| Protected Attribute | Legislation | Key Provisions |
|---------------------|------------|----------------|
| Age | Age Discrimination Act 2004 (Cth) | Prohibits discrimination in employment, education, access to premises, goods, services, and facilities |
| Sex, gender identity, intersex status, sexual orientation, marital status, pregnancy | Sex Discrimination Act 1984 (Cth) | Prohibits discrimination and harassment on the basis of sex and related attributes |
| Race, colour, descent, national or ethnic origin, immigration status | Racial Discrimination Act 1975 (Cth) | Prohibits discrimination based on race in all areas of public life |
| Disability (physical, intellectual, psychiatric, sensory, neurological, learning) | Disability Discrimination Act 1992 (Cth) | Prohibits discrimination against persons with disabilities; requires reasonable adjustments |
| Political opinion, religion, social origin | Australian Human Rights Commission Act 1986 (Cth) | Broader protections under the AHRC framework |

### 3.1 Proxy Discrimination

AI systems may discriminate indirectly through proxy variables. {{ business_name }} must audit for proxy discrimination where seemingly neutral features correlate with protected attributes, including but not limited to:

- Postcode as a proxy for race or socioeconomic status
- Name or language as a proxy for national origin
- Social media activity as a proxy for political opinion or religion
- Employment gaps as a proxy for disability, pregnancy, or caring responsibilities

