## 4. Audit Methodology

### 4.1 Phase 1 — Data Audit

| Step | Activity | Output |
|------|----------|--------|
| 1.1 | Inventory all training data sources used by in-scope AI systems | Data source register |
| 1.2 | Assess whether training data contains protected attribute information (directly or via proxy) | Protected attribute mapping |
| 1.3 | Evaluate training data representativeness across demographic groups | Representation analysis report |
| 1.4 | Identify historical biases embedded in training data (e.g., past discriminatory decisions) | Historical bias assessment |
| 1.5 | Review data labelling processes for subjective or inconsistent labels | Labelling quality report |

### 4.2 Phase 2 — Output Testing

| Step | Activity | Output |
|------|----------|--------|
| 2.1 | Generate synthetic test cases spanning all protected attribute groups | Test dataset |
| 2.2 | Submit test cases through the AI system and record outcomes | Raw results |
| 2.3 | Perform statistical analysis of outcome distribution across groups | Statistical analysis report |
| 2.4 | Identify outcome patterns that correlate with protected attributes | Correlation analysis |
| 2.5 | Test edge cases and intersectional groups (e.g., older women with disability) | Intersectional analysis |

### 4.3 Phase 3 — Disparate Impact Analysis

Apply the **four-fifths rule** as a threshold indicator: if the selection rate for any protected group is less than 80% of the selection rate for the most favoured group, disparate impact may exist.

| Metric | Calculation | Threshold |
|--------|------------|-----------|
| Selection rate ratio | (Selection rate of disadvantaged group) / (Selection rate of most favoured group) | >= 0.8 (four-fifths) |
| Odds ratio | Odds of positive outcome for disadvantaged group / Odds for favoured group | 0.8 - 1.25 acceptable range |
| Statistical significance | Chi-squared test or equivalent | p < 0.05 requires investigation |

