## 9. Regulatory Alignment

| Regulation / Guidance | Requirement | This Procedure |
|-----------------------|------------|----------------|
| AI Ethics Principle 2 (Fairness) | AI systems should be inclusive and accessible, not involving unfair discrimination | Comprehensive bias testing methodology and remediation |
| Privacy Act 1988 — APP 3 | Collection of sensitive information requires consent and must be necessary | Data audit identifies sensitive attribute collection in training data |
| Privacy Act 1988 — APP 6 | Use and disclosure for primary purpose or reasonably expected secondary purpose | Ensures AI outputs do not discriminate in ways outside collection purpose |
| POLA Act 2024 | Transparency in automated decision-making; reasonable steps to prevent harm | Disparate impact analysis, human review activation, affected individual assessment |
| Age Discrimination Act 2004 | No discrimination on the basis of age | Age-based outcome testing in Phase 2 |
| Sex Discrimination Act 1984 | No discrimination on the basis of sex, gender identity, or related attributes | Gender-based outcome testing in Phase 2 |
| Racial Discrimination Act 1975 | No discrimination on the basis of race | Race and ethnicity outcome testing in Phase 2 |
| Disability Discrimination Act 1992 | No discrimination on the basis of disability; reasonable adjustments | Disability-based testing; accessibility review of AI interfaces |
{% if tranche2_aware %}| POLA Act Tranche 2 (anticipated) | Mandatory bias testing for high-risk AI systems | This procedure is designed to meet anticipated Tranche 2 requirements |{% endif %}
| OAIC Oct 2024 | Organisations must assess AI systems for discrimination risk | Scheduled and event-triggered testing framework |

